title: IS Security and Assurance
comments: An examination of the concepts, technologies, and applications of security and assurance in information systems.  Topics include the security threats against information systems; tools used by intruders; computing platforms and security; encryption; securing the transaction and the server; audit tools to detect intrusions; responses to attacks; legal, ethical and international issues; and the future of information systems security and assurance.

subject: ARCH
title: Architecture and Culture
comments: Architecture and Culture: Buildings, Equity and Climate. Interdisciplinary and cross-cultural study of architecture and its context - fundamental architectural ideas, how and why buildings are built, how spaces are occupied and by whom, and how external forces (such as social, political, economic, and environmental) inform architecture’s construction and occupation. Examine key buildings from cultures around the world through architectural artifacts, texts, and drawings, employing both disciplinary and interdisciplinary perspectives. Analyze how these buildings operated within diverse cultures to investigate the mutual influence between architecture and its context over time. Develop coherent, evidence-based arguments, drawing on insights from both discipline-specific and interdisciplinary approaches. Develop recommendations for inclusive, equitable, and climate-responsive architecture. Our buildings take a lot of time, labor, and energy to construct. How and why we build them, who gets to use our buildings, and how our buildings impact the planet are as important to architecture as the appearance of buildings that have survived over time. In this course, we’ll explore things beyond aesthetics that have shaped buildings from the past and present, like economics and politics, so we can address big challenges like fighting climate change and designing inclusive spaces.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: Energy & Daylight Sim
comments: Energy & Daylight Simulation Undergraduates only. Graduates use ARCH 5064 Achieving the optimal design isn't always guaranteed by good intentions alone. Sometimes, relying solely on intuition and general guidelines falls short in making well-informed decisions. This course is designed to introduce students to the use of several advanced building simulation tools, including the COVE tool (Energy Simulation), Grasshopper (Climate Report), and Climate Studio (Daylight simulation). The course will fill the gap between qualitative and quantitative aspects of design, considering the user experience in the daylight simulation stage. The primary focus is on designing and optimizing sustainable building systems through energy modeling in the early design stages to reduce environmental impact and enhance energy efficiency. Students will gain an understanding of the natural forces and human comfort factors that drive sustainable systems, as well as the various systems and cycles of our planet, including energy, atmosphere, and climate. No prior experience is required, and all licenses will be provided.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: Rhino & Photoshop
comments: Digital Modeling & Post-production: Rhinoceros 2D & 3D + Adobe Photoshop. Undergraduates Only. Graduates use ARCH 5064. This course blends conceptual design in Rhinoceros with post-production techniques in Adobe Photoshop, equipping students with a well-rounded digital skill set. Beginning with 2D drafting, students will progress to intricate 3D modeling in Rhino, gaining expertise in precision modeling. The course will then transition to Photoshop, where students will refine their designs using advanced effects and visual enhancements. With hands-on exercises and project-based learning, this course is designed to help students elevate their digital design capabilities.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: ICDF
comments: Undergraduates only. Graduates use ARCH 5064 The Integrated Computational Design & Fabrication (ICDF) course introduces students to the intersection of computational design and digital fabrication in architecture. Students will gain hands-on experience with Grasshopper 3D, learning to design free-form objects/structures and create prototypes using advanced digital fabrication tools like Robotic Arm, CNC machines, and 3D printers. Through weekly modeling assignments and group projects, students will design and prototype an installation, integrating computational thinking with practical fabrication techniques. In the last month, we make one of the projects on a real scale. The course aims to familiarize students with digital tools and processes, highlighting how fabrication capabilities influence architectural design and construction.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: BIM: Revit & Enscape Essen
comments: Architectureal BIM & Visualization: Introduction & Essentials of Revit and Enscape Undergraduates Only. Graduates use ARCH 5064. This course introduces the core concepts and tools of Building Information Modeling (BIM) using Autodesk Revit, alongside visualization techniques in Enscape. Students will learn to create, analyze, and present architectural designs in both technical and visually compelling ways. Through detailed explanations and hands-on exercises, students will develop a strong understanding of these tools, progressing from fundamental techniques to more complex applications. Whether you're new to BIM or looking to enhance your skills, this course provides an excellent foundation for unlocking creative potential.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: Pencil Drawing
comments: Pencil Drawing For Enhancing Creativity and Artistic Confidence Open to all majors in AAD. For force adds, please email Vern Ferguson vernf@vt.edu. This course will give students a fundamental understanding of free-hand pencil drawing and analog rendering. It will be valuable to students who have prior experience in fine arts and those with little to no knowledge of the field. Our subject of observation will not be architecture per se, but rather organic structures, plant anatomy, and landscape.   The semester will be roughly divided into two parts. The first half will focus on shade, shadow, texture, and form. Together, we will draw still-life objects in and around our studio space, working to complete simple weekly exercises on small 8.5x11 bristol paper. The second half will be slightly more open-ended and long-term: having established core principles of technique, students will be asked to choose their subject matter and then arrange it in a visually compelling composition on 18x24 bristol paper. There will be two of these final compositions, and students will have three weeks to complete each of them.   The pedagogical atmosphere will imitate that of a Japanese art studio, or Bijustsu. Our pencils will, at all times, be as sharp as needle points. We will emphasize clarity, craft, and an obsessive precision that borders on near-perfection.

subject: ARCH

comments: Undergraduates only. Graduates use ARCh 5115 This course introduces architecture students to the capabilities of Unreal Engine 5 for architectural visualization. Students will learn how to create immersive environments, render high-quality images, cinematics, and be introduced to blueprint coding language. Through a blend of technical tutorials and projects, students will explore lighting, materials, and real-time rendering techniques. By the end of this course, students will be equipped to utilize Unreal Engine 5 for architectural presentations and design exploration.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: Mapping the Built
comments: Undergraduates only. Graduates use ARCH 5116 The course is an introduction to the science and art of cartography, including the conceptual framework of the cartographic method. Development of the skills necessary to create maps to be used in the reading, analysis, and interpretation of spatial arrangements, with an emphasis on data collection, evaluation, and synthesis using applicable technologies such as Geographic Information Systems (GIS). Analysis and synthesis of results will be explored that consider the impact of using platform technologies at varying scales in the planning and design process, on the built environment.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: Machine: Intro. Robots
comments: Undergraduates only. Graduates use ARCH 5064. Welcome, Machine: Intro. Robots in Arch, Art, Des., & Constr. Digital design and robotic fabrication technologies have become integral to the discourse surrounding contemporary practice. These tools have afforded new opportunities and challenges related to the realization of design and creative output. The course includes weekly lectures, discussions, and/or hands-on workshops. Intended to be a first point-of-contact for the use of industrial robotics, the course provides introduction to digital workflows, tooling, and robot operation. Lectures include historic overview of mechanization, fundamentals of fabrication and manufacturing, strategic customization, digital and physical prototyping, digital simulation, introduction to robotic systems, introduction to product development, production economics, in-situ automation, etc. The course utilized the CDR Design Robotics Studio and Laboratories and each student should develop the confidence, knowledge, and skill to use these machines safely and effectively.

subject: ARCH
title: TS: Futuring Healthcare
comments: Design can play an important role in the health and wellness of our communities. Architects, artists, and designers enrolled in this new course will benefit from an introduction to healthcare from an expert and medical professional, Dr. Andy Muelenaer. Students will learn about the services and stakeholders important to medical spaces -- from large hospitals to rural settings, in the USA and abroad -- as each context comes with its own unique challenges. Students will complete the course with a working knowledge of vocabulary important to healthcare systems, a deeper knowledge of the considerations in built environments that support community wellness, and a patient and provider centric approach to problem solving in the healthcare industry.  The course includes discussions, research techniques, and onsite visits aimed at students new to the topic of healthcare. It will conclude with a case study in a pediatric setting regarding Hippotherapy, a therapeutic approach that uses the unique movement of a horse as a tool to help individuals with physical, sensory, and cognitive challenges. Consider for every 100 new design jobs being created in the United States in 2025-26, 50,000 new jobs will be added to healthcare. Empower yourself to work in this exciting and important environment as a practitioner in Architecture, Arts, and/or Design! No prerequisites required, open to all majors.

subject: ARCH
title: Topics in Comp Appl Design
comments: In this course on acoustic experiences, students will discover how acoustics can enhance human life and well-being. They will study the science of sound and examine how people perceive it in various settings, accounting for cognitive and cultural factors. Working in teams, students will analyze selected acoustic environments and design aural experiences intended to boost positive emotions, productivity, creativity, or a sense of community. Through engagement with the broader community and in-class reflections, they will connect their theoretical understanding to real-world applications. The evaluations and discussions throughout the course will establish a foundation for designing and assessing their final acoustic experience projects.

subject: ARCH
title: ARCH & Western Thought
comments: Methods in Architectural History (a.k.a Movements in Architecture and Western Thought) The history methods course will address approaches to the writing of architectural history, particularly in terms of philosophical issues. The course will ask: why we write architectural history; how history relates to contemporary practice; how our present concerns shape our descriptions of the past and how our descriptions of the past shape our present self-understanding; what is unique about architectural history in contrast to history as such; what the relationship is between history and theory and between history and criticism; and how we understand questions around facts versus values, evidence versus narrative and interpretation, and objectivity versus subjectivity. During the course, students will become familiar with various ideas and approaches that have underpinned the writing of architectural history—the German tradition of Kulturwissenschaft, metahistory and conceptual history, critical history, archeology and genealogy, micro history and the annals school of long durée history, hermeneutics, subaltern histories, materialist and technical histories, cultural techniques and media histories, global history, new historicism, and universal history. The course is required for Masters and PhD students in history, theory and criticism, but open to all M.Arch students and upper year B.arch students. Those architectural design students joining the course will learn how our ideas about architecture have been constructed over the past three hundred years.

subject: ART
title: East Asian Water Media
comments: ARC fee $80.   East Asian Water Media is a studio art course for non-majors. No prior art experience is necessary. Students use Sumi ink and bamboo brushes to create a variety of drawings and paintings, learning both traditional methods and contemporary approaches. Sumi ink paintings depict the essence of an object or scene rather than its outward appearances. Sumi ink painting is a contemplative form of expression that emphasizes self-cultivation. It has been practiced in East Asia for over a thousand years.

It is an introductory course that will provide a basic understanding of painting media. This is an oil painting course. Students will study painting through inquiry-based projects that require research into areas of global, regional, and/or local and personal concern, as well as reflect the core Pathways principals of Integration, Inclusivity, and Relevance. Students will learn the basic qualities of paint, brushes, and surfaces from historical and contemporary points of view, and learn how to manipulate and control the materials.

subject: ART
title: TS: Matrl Culture of Beverage
comments: This class will explore the material culture surrounding consuming beverages in a global context. Themes explored in the class will include water, chocolate, tea, coffee, wine, and beer. Within these themes material culture that is discussed might include vessels used to drink, vessels used to store/transport, or objects used in connection to production of the beverages. Each unit will explore a select range of cultures who interacted with that class of beverage; cultures explored can range from ancient to contemporary. For example, when discussing cultures who consumed cacao in beverages, both Maya and eighteenth-century European chocolate pots will be addressed. Students will have the opportunity to choose cultures that interest them to research in connection to the themes of beverages discussed in the course.

subject: ART
title: TS: Monsters & Marvels
comments: A study of the material and visual culture of a variety of monsters and marvels through history: witches, zombies, werewolves, the wild man, oddities, myths, legends, heroes and more. What does it mean in art and society when something is exceptional, either monstrous or marvelous? How were these forms collected and exhibited from cabinets of curiosity to circuses? This class examines monsters and marvels as part of the human quest to organize and control the unknown, remarkable, or the different.

subject: ART
title: TS: Exhibiting Animals
comments: This course examines the role of animals in the visual arts from 1500 to the present. It attends to diverse historical and cultural contexts, and considers a wide range of approaches to representing animal life, collaborating with animal subjects, and/or utilizing animal-derived materials. Readings, discussions, and assignments emphasize the politics of animal art and display, particularly their relevance to histories of race, gender, sexuality, and colonialism. The course also introduces students to critical animal studies, ecocriticism, and new materialism, illuminating how the so-called “animal turn” in the humanities is currently reshaping contemporary art, cinema, art historical inquiry, objects conservation, and curatorial practice.

subject: CEM
title: Global Design and Construction
comments: A collaborative approach to apply engineering systems and design to solve local issues. Design, engineering, & construction focused on social responsibility and sustainability in Appalachia/southwest Va. Multi-disciplinary teamwork requiring identification of client needs and design considerations, development of site layouts, selection of resources, management of schedule, cost, materials, personnel, quality, and job site safety. The $ 400 course fee includes transportation, meals, and lodging for two (2) weekend projects. Projects are in Dickenson County (Appalachia/southwest VA) on Oct 10-12, Nov 7-9, and/or Nov. 14-16.

subject: CINE
title: Intro to Cinema Production
comments: This course encompasses the basic technology of film practice, including the use of video cameras, simple lighting, sound recording, and digital editing. You will learn the basics of film language and aesthetics, shot composition, continuity, as well as learning to approach sound and image creatively.  Throughout this semester you will work individually using introductory technologies to develop your critical skills as a viewer, maker and reader. The ultimate goal of the course is to develop both technical and conceptual skills through the use of film screenings, lectures, demonstrations and readings in order to successfully put your thoughts and ideas onto film.

subject: CINE
title: Intro to Cinema Production
comments: This course encompasses the basic technology of film practice, including the use of video cameras, simple lighting, sound recording, and digital editing. You will learn the basics of film language and aesthetics, shot composition, continuity, as well as learning to approach sound and image creatively.  Throughout this semester you will work individually using introductory technologies to develop your critical skills as a viewer, maker and reader. The ultimate goal of the course is to develop both technical and conceptual skills through the use of film screenings, lectures, demonstrations and readings in order to successfully put your thoughts and ideas onto film.

subject: CINE
title: TS: Cinematography
comments: This intermediate-level Cinematography course builds on foundational principles of motion picture lighting and optics in order to deepen students’ understanding of the technical, artistic, and storytelling aspects of the craft. Students will engage in hands-on projects, critical analysis, collaborative and individual exercises, readings, viewings, and discussions to refine their skills and develop a personal style. Key topics include: lighting, camera, composition, movement, color, exposure, story alignment, and more.

subject: ECE
title: SS: Quantum Engineering
comments: A- F grading only. The audit option is NOT available. COURSE DESCRIPTION. Introduction to fundamental concepts and engineering principles of quantum physics, quantum computing, quantum communication, and quantum sensing. The quantum physics section includes quantum states, superposition, entanglement, quantum measurements. The quantum computing section includes quantum bits, gates, circuits, algorithms, and quantum error correction. The quantum communication section includes toy models for quantum key distribution and quantum teleportation. The quantum sensing section includes solid-state quantum defect sensors and single photon detection. Software quantum simulators will also be introduced, providing hands-on experience with quantum gates, measurements, and algorithms. (3H, 3C)

subject: ECE
title: SS: 5G-Advanced, O-RAN, and 6G
comments: A-F only. The Audit option is NOT available. Prerequisite: 5664, Cellular Communication Systems. COURSE DESCRIPTION:  The fifth-generation (5G) wireless technology is expected to revolutionize multiple industries. 5G is being enhanced with new capabilities.  This course discusses new 5G capabilities such as a Non-Terrestrial Network (NTN), Integrated Access and Backhaul (IAB), sidelink, and Vehicle-to-Everything (V2X) communications. Wireless Internet of Things (IoT) technologies such as enhanced Machine Type Communications (eMTC) and Narrowband-IoT are also explained. The 5G-based Radio Access Network (RAN) can be deployed using the architecture defined by the Open-RAN (O-RAN) Alliance. Such O-RAN architecture is illustrated. The O-RAN architecture derives its intelligence using applications such as xApps. This course provides hands-on experience in developing xApps. 5G will evolve to 6G around 2030. The course introduces the vision and requirements of 6G and discusses key technologies that are expected to play an important role in 6G.

subject: ECE
title: SS: Data Engineering Project
comments: A-F only. The audit option is not available. This section is for Master of Information Technology (MIT) students only. Prerequisite: Graduate standing. Fundamentals of data engineering. The role of data engineer. Data engineering lifecycle. Data quality and valuation. Data provenance. Data generation, ingestion, transformation, storage, serving Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning (AI/ML), visualization, and business analytics. Automation and task orchestration. Data systems. E(xtract)T(ransform)L(oad) data. Build, test, maintain data pipelines. Data lakes. Real-world problems with emphasis on end-to-end engineering solutions. Cloud services and open-source data engines/platforms. Engineering portfolio.  (3H, 3C).

subject: ECE
title: SS: Data Engineering Project
comments: A-F only. The audit option is not available. This section is for EE-CPE MEng students only. Prerequisite: Graduate standing. COURSE DESCRIPTION: Fundamentals of data engineering. The role of data engineer. Data engineering lifecycle. Data quality and valuation. Data provenance. Data generation, ingestion, transformation, storage, serving Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning (AI/ML), visualization, and business analytics. Automation and task orchestration. Data systems. E(xtract)T(ransform)L(oad) data. Build, test, maintain data pipelines. Data lakes. Real-world problems with emphasis on end-to-end engineering solutions. Cloud services and open-source data engines/platforms. Engineering portfolio.  (3H, 3C).

subject: ECE
title: SS: Critical Eng Emerging Tech
comments: A-F only. The audit option is not available. Master of Information Technology (MIT) students only. COURSE DESCRIPTION: Complex sociotechnical systems and unintended consequences. Engineering profession and society. Frameworks for critical engineering practice. Spread of innovative ideas. Risk, precaution, and innovation constraints. Definitions, mechanisms, and case studies of the governance of existing technologies, such as cybersecurity, Internet, and information technology. Characteristics and examples of emerging technologies. Emerging technology governance frameworks and tools. Hype, expectations, and technology assessment. Governance case studies of specific emerging technologies, such as artificial intelligence, nanotechnology, quantum computing, autonomous vehicles, and neurotechnology. Technologies of democracy and public interest technologies. Governing technology into the future. Pre: Graduate Standing. (3H, 3C).

subject: ECE
title: SS: AIML-MIMO-NextGen Wireless
comments: A-F grades only. The audit option is not available. Students are to log on at the time of class. COURSE DESCRIPTION: This course will introduce multiple-input-multiple-output (MIMO) technologies in modern cellular networks and machine learning-enabled MIMO operations. Emphasis will be placed on the key MIMO operation components in 3GPP 5G NR such as reference signal design, MIMO channel estimation, MIMO channel state information feedback, MIMO transmission operation, distributed MIMO, and MIMO receive processing. Efficient machine learning tools will be introduced to enable learning-based MIMO operations in 5G and NextG—Prerequisite: graduate standing.

subject: ECE
title: SS: Industry Topics and Prof
comments: P/F only. The audit option is NOT available—virtual sync section. This course is for Master of Engineering (MEng) and Industry Cohort students only. Prerequisite: Graduate standing. COURSE DESCRIPTION: Research and development methods for Engineers. Presentation of current industry and research topics in Electrical and Computer Engineering by local and visiting industry leaders and scholars. Systematic approaches to Project planning, organization and implementation. Introduction to literature searches and library resources. An introduction to patent law and intellectual property as it applies to academic and industrial research. Ethical standards in teaching, mentoring, and professional activities, including issues of ethics and integrity including plagiarism, text reuse, and data falsification. (3H, 3C).

title: SS: Economics Career Prep
comments: Preparation for professional success by focusing on career development, academic strategy, and life after academics as it relates to economics.  Students will learn how to navigate the economics job market, including roles in economic research, consulting, policy, and data analytics.  Focus on crafting economics-focused job market materials, develop interview skills specific to economics positions, introduce effective networking strategies.Pre-Reqs: ECON 1004, 2005, 2006, and Sophomore or Junior status.

subject: ECON
title: TS: Rockonmics: ECON of Music
comments: There’s a lot of interesting economics going on behind the scenes in the music industry: It is among the first industries to be disrupted by new technologies. Important network effects either elevate artists to stardom or lead them to obscurity. And because music taps into our emotions and social connections, behavioral economics plays a key role in how we produce, consume, and value it.

subject: ECON
title: TS: Cryptoeconomics
comments: This course examines the emerging field of cryptoeconomics, exploring how economic incentives and cryptographic tools create novel economic systems. Students will analyze blockchain protocols, token economics, decentralized finance applications, and related policy frameworks. The course synthesizes concepts from economics, game theory, computer science, and finance to provide a comprehensive understanding of this rapidly evolving domain.

subject: ECON
title: TS: AI-Driven Analysis in ECON
comments: Introduction to the use of AI-powered tools in practical business applications, with a focus on prompt engineering techniques to improve economic data analysis. Students will gain hands-on experience in data discovery, cleaning, and exploratory data analysis using AI as well as ethical considerations around the use of AI. Prerequisites: ECON 2005 or ECON 2006; Sophomore standing or above

subject: ECON
title: TS: Startups
comments: The course explores how core economic principles apply to the fast-paced and uncertain world of startups. Examine why most startups fail, what drives the rare few that succeed, and how market dynamics, timing, competition, and incentives shape outcomes. Through real-world examples and hands-on projects, students will learn how to identify problems worth solving, develop viable business models, and analyze ventures from multiple stakeholder perspectives. Pre-Req: Must have at least 75 hours completed.

subject: HIST
title: Intro to World History
comments: Fulfills CLE Areas 3 and 7. Fulfills Pathways Concepts 2 or 3.

subject: HIST
title: Virginia Indigenous History
comments: There is more to Indigenous people in Virginia than Matoaka (commonly known as Pocahontas). This course takes students through a ride and exploration of Virginia's Indigenous History from time immemorial to 2018. Students will learn about the 11 Nations in the commonwealth and get a firm understanding on the three major cultural groups they belong to: Iroquoian, Algonquian, and Eastern Siouan. This course will also guide students through the arrival of Europeans on Virginia's coast and the implications of their continued presence and western expansion.

subject: HIST
title: TS: WWII in Postwar America
comments: Topic: World War II in Postwar American Culture. This course explores the manifold ways in which World War II infused American culture in the decades since the conflict ended. Using film, novels, art, television broadcasts, and other media, we will focus much our inquiry on “citizen-soldiers” and veterans, as people and family members, icons and cultural touchstones, protagonists and living memorials, and as a quietly vanishing generation. What do portrayals of World War II, soldiers, and veterans tell us about who we are as a nation, society, and culture? Fulfills Pathways concepts 2 and 7 and Depth Studies II.

subject: HIST
title: TS: Environmental Hist of VT
comments: This research course explores the environmental history of Virginia Tech's campus, beginning before campus existed. We will consider different ways that people have used and changed this land, and how the environment has shaped or constrained decisions about this place. Major topics include the burial of a creek to build the Drillfield, the impact of floods, changes in local plants and animals, and how VT's increased construction and growing population have impacted areas beyond campus. Students will conduct research in various archives around campus and present their discoveries at the end of the semester. Pathway Concept Area(s): 2 Critical Thinking Humanities, 3 Reasoning in Social Sciences, 10 Ethical Reasoning

subject: HIST
title: TS: Race and Real Estate
comments: How much is a house worth? What is a title company? What does it mean to buy or sell a piece of property? How do you make money doing it? This class will explore the history and foundations of real estate in the United States, from the earliest purchasers of land to the most significant and controversial transactions and developments.

subject: HIST
title: Topics Hist Data Soc Context
comments: This course explores the history of cholera in the global context of the nineteenth century, with particular attention to outbreaks in Europe, United States, Russia, India, and the Middle East. Students will complete individual and collaborative research projects in ways that advance understanding of the human dimensions of infectious diseases.   The course will fulfill Pathways 5f, Quantitative and Computational Thinking, requirements through the recording of vital statistics, the creation of charts, maps, and tables, and critical interpretation of the meaning of data in social context. The course will fulfill Pathways 1f, Discourse, through writing research papers, making presentations, preparing posters, creative writing, and data visualization exercises. The course may substitute for a history course required for the Russian Area Studies minor.

subject: HIST
title: Crit Reading/Analysis in Hist
comments: Living in a Material World: Can we write history based on a sack with nine embroidered lines? How about bird poop? Or rice? This class explores the history of material culture in a global context. Our readings will take us from the United States, to Africa, South America, and to the Pacific guano islands. We will examine how historians have used material goods to offer new examinations of the past.

subject: HIST
title: History Research Seminar
comments: Venice, a city frozen in time. Originally a Byzantine outpost in the West, Venice rose over the centuries to become an independent maritime power, and at times, an ally of Byzantium, at other times a formidable enemy. After the disastrous Fourth Crusade (1204), Venice created a maritime empire stretching from the Adriatic to the Black Sea regions. After the conquest of Constantinople by the Ottoman Turks in 1453, Venice assumed the mantle of protector over the dismembered Byzantine Empire and led the resistance to the western expansion of the Turks.   Through primary documents and images, this seminar will trace the history of Venice from the fifth century AD to the present; her rise to world prominence in Italy and the Mediterranean; her political, social, military, and religious institutions; the brilliance of her art & architecture; and the modern environmental crisis that may eventually doom Venice and her lagoon.

subject: JMC
title: Topics Multimedia Journalism
comments: TOPIC: Crime, Conspiracy and Cults in Media. Psychological factors for the audience of crime, conspiracy and cult media, including podcasts, documentaries, and “news” websites; personality factors associated with risk for beliefs in conspiracy and cults, how people get into a conspiracy mindset, and what is effective at breaking them out; ethical ways to produce media on crime, conspiracy, and cults, that don’t exploit the victims or audience, or put more people at risk for being pulled into those communities. This course can be substituted for Theory Elective for MJ majors.

subject: JMC
title: Topics Multimedia Journalism
comments: Must have completed COMM 2024 and either COMM 2034, ADV 2034, CMST 2034 or JMC 2034.   Can be used for Application Elective for MJ majors. TOPIC:  Drone Journalism This course provides an introduction to the use of drone aircraft for visual communication in journalism, advertising, and public relations. It will cover essential FAA rules and regulations, safe drone operations and flight, drone photography, and drone videography. We will discuss drone law and ethics, and will explore the most effective and aesthetically compelling uses of drones for photography and video.

subject: MATH
title: SS: Topological Data Analysis
comments: Introduction to Data, shape of Data, Structures on spaces of Barcodes, Introduction to Chain complexes as both geometric and combinatorial objects and Z_2-Homology, Homology on Data sets, Persistence homology. Suggested Prerequisites: MATH 3144 or (MATH 2114 and MATH 3124) or (MATH 2114 and CMDA 3605). Students who have taken MATH 2114 and a different 3000-level MATH should speak with the course instructor.

subject: MATH
title: Coding Theory and Applications
comments: This course oﬀers an introduction to Coding Theory, which explores the principles behind reliable communications. The subject lies at the intersection of mathematics, computer science, and engineering, and provides tools to detect and correct errors in communication systems. Coding theory plays a central role in digital communication, data storage, cryptography, and quantum error correction.

subject: MATH
title: Topics in Topology & Geometry
comments: Algebraic Geometry 1

subject: MATH
title: Topics in Applied Mathematics
comments: Title:ROMS for Fluids.  This course introduces students to the reduced order modeling of fluid flows. Assuming minimal background, the course emphasizes the strong connection among the modeling, analysis, and computations of various reduced order modeling approaches for engineering and geophysical flows. The course is divided into two main areas: fluids and reduced order models (ROMs).  Topics in the fluids area include the Navier-Stokes equations and the quasi-geostrophic equations (QGE), as well as building block systems (e.g., the Poisson, heat, convection-diffusion, Stokes, and Burgers equations). The connections of these equations to the physical and computational worlds are emphasized. Topics in the ROM area include the proper orthogonal decomposition (POD) and the reduced basis method (RBM) for parameterized systems.  Both the development and the numerical analysis of these methods are covered.  Finally, these different ROMs are used for an efficient and relatively accurate numerical simulation of realistic engineering and geophysical flows. A particular emphasis will be on ROMs for turbulent flows and enabling methodologies (e.g., stabilization and closure modeling).

subject: MATH
title: Topics in Applied Mathematics
comments: Title:Stochastic Dynamics.  This course will provide a broad introduction to the actively evolving field of nonlinear stochastic dynamics, focusing on the basic mathematics and computational tools in the study of such systems. The following topics will be covered: Basic concepts of Probability, Brownian motion, Stochastic differential equations and related numerical simulation techniques, Stochastic bifurcations and noise-induced chaos. The course material will be self-contained. The focus will be on establishing a basic and intuitive understanding of the concepts involved.

subject: MATH
title: Numer Analy and Softw
comments: Focus will be on iterative methods for solving large scale linear systems and eigenvalue problems which play a fundamental role in realistic simulation and optimization problems. The principal and popular iterative methods and preconditioners for the solution of linear systems will be discussed together with the analysis of their convergence behavior.

subject: MATH
title: Model and Sim of Bio Systems

subject: MATH
title: Optimization, Machine Learning
comments: Optimization plays a fundamental role in engineering, science, data analytics, and machine learning. We will cover the fundamentals of optimization, considering both important classes of problems and important classes of algorithms and their underlying theory. We will consider both convex and general nonlinear optimization methods with and without constraints, nonlinear least squares problems, parameter estimation, and ill-posed inverse problems, and various methods to solve such problems, including line-search and trust-region methods, the closely related Levenberg-Marquardt method, Gauss-Newton approaches, (nonlinear) Conjugate Gradients, and quasi-Newton methods, as well as several stochastic optimization techniques and randomization to make very large-scale problems (including machine learning) tractable. We then consider how to apply these techniques effectively to large machine learning problems using a range of ML approaches, such as various classes of deep neural networks and how to train them (optimization and regularization). We will consider several mathematical models that have recently been proposed for analysis of deep learning as well some more recent approaches to ML and open problems.  We will demonstrate these methods for several applications.

subject: ME
title: SS: Soft Robotics
comments: The recent advances in biomimicry, material science, design methodology, and control theory has enabled us to build soft robots collaborating closely with humans in unstructured and dynamic working conditions. These robots are typically made of soft materials exhibiting low elastic modulus and high strain before failure, making them safer and more versatile than the traditional rigid-linked robots for tasks like minimally invasive surgery, search/rescue, rehabilitation, and manufacturing. This course aims to introduce this rapidly emerging field, survey the different soft robot design, fabrication, and control techniques, and challenge the students to fabricate their soft robots to achieve a sophisticated manipulation /locomotion task.

subject: MKTG
title: Sales Technology
comments: Course focus is on the integration of technology and data analytics to advance sales.  Study of how technology is leveraged in the social sales process which includes how to successfully utilize technology in social selling situations.  Emphasis given to Customer Relationship Management (CRM) strategies, benefits, operations, and application across the customer life cycle.  Students demonstrate proficiency in CRM technology, through experiential learning by earning Salesforce, Hubspot and Smartfox badges.

subject: PHIL
title: Knowledge and Reality
comments: Are your thoughts inside of your brain? Can you ever be completely certain of anything? Are you the same person now as you were when you were three years old? Is time travel possible? Is anything bigger than infinity? What is it like to be a bat? What is the difference between bull and a lie? Do you have free will? Can God brew a cup of tea too hot for Him to drink? In this course, you will explore these and other questions, and learn how to debate them in a philosophically rigorous way.

comments: What is knowledge and what is it possible to know? Is the world of experience reality or the illusion that obscures it? Is there a God, and what makes things good or bad? This course explores these problems in ancient and modern philosophy.

subject: PHIL
title: Morality and Justice
comments: This course is an introduction to ethics, in which we aspire to get a better understanding of right and wrong. We begin by asking what makes a life good. We then discuss some theories of right and wrong and explore concepts of right and wrong in particular situations. Lastly, we question whether right and wrong even exist in the first place.

subject: PHIL
title: Morality and Justice
comments: This is an introduction to ethics course. We will begin by exploring what morality is and what moral judgements are about. We will then look at several theories of right and wrong action. The second half of the course will center on real-world ethical problems (e.g., animal ethics, abortion, global poverty, and triage). Here, we will ask: what, when confronted with these situations, should you do?

subject: PHIL
title: Morality and Justice
comments: This course acquaints students with three basic ethical theories—utilitarianism, deontic ethics, and virtue ethics—using both ancient and contemporary readings. Along the way, students will discuss problems related to such moral concepts as duty, justice, truth, rights, honesty, and happiness in life.

subject: PHIL
title: Critical Thinking
comments: If you want to believe true things and disbelieve false things, you should think about whether you have good grounds (reason, evidence) for belief. This course is about exactly that. Since grounds usually can be put in the form of an argument, we'll cover arguments and their anatomy, how to reconstruct them, and how to tell whether they constitute good grounds. We'll also cover "trading" arguments with other people, and how to lower the chance of being deceived.

subject: PHIL
title: Critical Thinking
comments: If you want to believe true things and disbelieve false things, you should think about whether you have good grounds (reason, evidence) for belief. This course is about exactly that. Since grounds usually can be put in the form of an argument, we'll cover arguments and their anatomy, how to reconstruct them, and how to tell whether they constitute good grounds. We'll also cover "trading" arguments with other people, and how to lower the chance of being deceived.

subject: PHIL
title: Ancient/Medieval Philosophy
comments: Socrates (470-399BCE), Plato (427-347BCE), and Aristotle (384-322BCE) were philosophers in ancient Greece, in the city of Athens. They are founding thinkers in the Western philosophical tradition. We will study their ideas on ethics, knowledge, reality, the soul, and the meaning of life. We will look at how their ideas grew out of their cultural setting, and also how their ideas provoke us to think about these topics now. Among the questions to be explored: What is the basis for morality? How do we define terms like “virtue” or “justice”? How do we know that, say, 2+2=4? What is the soul? Is it immortal? What are the best roles for reason and for emotion in our lives? How can we lead a good life? (Medieval Philosophy is covered in PHIL 2116.)

subject: PHIL
title: Global Ethics
comments: This course concerns urgent moral issues that will define the lives and livelihoods of 21st-century young adults. What will the world look like in 20 years, 50, or 100? How do we stem the growing tide of imperialism, oppression, and violence? What does it mean to be a global citizen? Why do so many have so little? How do we undo the legacies of colonialism? This class is discussion-based and makes heavy use of movies, shows, and social media, in addition to books and papers.

subject: PHIL
title: Global Ethics
comments: This course concerns urgent moral issues that will define the lives and livelihoods of 21st-century young adults. What will the world look like in 20 years, 50, or 100? How do we stem the growing tide of imperialism, oppression, and violence? What does it mean to be a global citizen? Why do so many have so little? How do we undo the legacies of colonialism? This class is discussion-based and makes heavy use of movies, shows, and social media, in addition to books and papers.

subject: PHIL
title: Global Ethics
comments: This course explores ethical concerns in a global context, including global poverty, climate change, autocratic governments, human rights, and international immigration. A primary goal of global ethics is to encourage reflection on what it means to live a good life and do the right thing when we identify forms of injustice across the globe or other kinds of global challenges. Thus, global ethics encourages reflection on how we are connected to others in a global community, and on the ethical implications this has for how we should live our lives—as consumers, as workers, as citizens, and as people with different lifestyles. The point of this course is not to indoctrinate you into any specific ethical viewpoints, but for you to develop your own as you engage thoughtfully with complex and controversial topics in global ethics.

subject: PHIL
title: Global Ethics
comments: This course requires students to engage in a philosophical analysis of global ethical issues. You will learn ethical theories, develop your critical thinking skills, and reflect on what it means for you to live an ethical life in a global context by considering issues such as global poverty, immigration, fast fashion, vegetarianism and veganism, climate change, and global health. Students will be guided through video lectures, readings, and additional online content (podcasts, videos), complete quizzes and argument papers, and contribute to weekly discussion forums.

subject: PHIL

subject: PHIL
title: Political Theory
comments: The course provides an overview of nearly 2000 years of Western Political thinking; it covers the period from the Ancient Greeks to early modern times, we investigate many different concepts, which still determine contemporary political language, with regard to their origins and transformations in political practice.

subject: PHIL
title: Political Theory
comments: This is an intermediate undergraduate course that exposes students to in-depth readings of seminal thinkers and texts in the modern history of political thought. The themes central to this course range from early contacts between European and indigenous American civilizations, humanist inquiries into the changing nature of society, historical accounts of the evolution of gender, social, and political hierarchies, as well as prophetic calls for the radical transformation of the individual. Thinkers studied will include: Bartolomé de las Casas, Niccolo Machiavelli, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Mary Wollstonecraft, and Friedrich Nietzsche, among others.

subject: PHIL
title: Biomedical Ethics
comments: This course requires students to engage in a philosophical analysis of ethical issues that arise in the context of medicine, healthcare, and biotechnology such as medical paternalism, medically assisted dying, abortion, “designer” babies, research with humans and animals, and health inequality. A high level of student involvement is expected for this class. Students will complete readings prior to each class, with class time focused on discussion and debate.

subject: PHIL
title: Biomedical Ethics
comments: This course requires students to engage in a philosophical analysis of ethical issues that arise in the context of medicine, healthcare, and biotechnology such as medical paternalism, medically assisted dying, abortion, “designer” babies, research with humans and animals, and health inequality. A high level of student involvement is expected for this class. Students will complete readings prior to each class, with class time focused on discussion and debate.

subject: PHIL
title: Modern Logic & Dev
comments: Broadly speaking, logic is the study of correct reasoning. Modern logic is almost synonymous with the symbolic representation of deductive reasoning, or reasoning with certainty. We will study a profoundly influential symbolic logic called First Order Logic (FOL). As we learn the rules of FOL and how to apply them to real arguments, we'll attend to the motivations for the often controversial choices made in choosing those rules during the construction of FOL. As we master the system, we will learn what FOL can do for us as a tool for reasoning in philosophy, mathematics, linguistics, and computer science. Finally, we will consider what FOL viewed as a mathematical model of reasoning has taught us about the limits of mathematics and deductive reason itself.

subject: PHIL
title: TS: Bureaucracy
comments: All students welcome. Pathways 2 and 3 approved. Course Information: This course explores a variety of questions concerning government bureaucracy in democratic political systems. Topics include positive and normative theories of delegation of authority to government agencies, bureaucratic structure, oversight, civil service systems, politicization, and accountability.

subject: PPE
title: Political Theory
comments: This is an intermediate undergraduate course that exposes students to in-depth readings of seminal thinkers and texts in the modern history of political thought. The themes central to this course range from early contacts between European and indigenous American civilizations, humanist inquiries into the changing nature of society, historical accounts of the evolution of gender, social, and political hierarchies, as well as prophetic calls for the radical transformation of the individual. Thinkers studied will include: Bartolomé de las Casas, Niccolo Machiavelli, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Mary Wollstonecraft, and Friedrich Nietzsche, among others.

subject: PPE

subject: PPE

comments: All students welcome. Pathways 2 and 3 approved. Course Information: This course explores a variety of questions concerning government bureaucracy in democratic political systems. Topics include positive and normative theories of delegation of authority to government agencies, bureaucratic structure, oversight, civil service systems, politicization, and accountability.

subject: PSCI
title: Study Abroad
comments: Study Abroad – Riva San Vitale, Switzerland This one-credit course will provide an introduction to the political thought of Niccolo Machiavelli in four two-hour seminar meetings. Two of these meetings will take place prior to a group excursion to Florence, Italy, in mid-September, and two meetings will follow the excursion.

title: Prof & Careers in PSCI & IS

subject: PSCI
title: Political Theory
comments: The course provides an overview of nearly 2000 years of Western Political thinking; it covers the period from the Ancient Greeks to early modern times, we investigate many different concepts, which still determine contemporary political language, with regard to their origins and transformations in political practice.

subject: PSCI
title: Political Theory
comments: This is an intermediate undergraduate course that exposes students to in-depth readings of seminal thinkers and texts in the modern history of political thought. The themes central to this course range from early contacts between European and indigenous American civilizations, humanist inquiries into the changing nature of society, historical accounts of the evolution of gender, social, and political hierarchies, as well as prophetic calls for the radical transformation of the individual. Thinkers studied will include: Bartolomé de las Casas, Niccolo Machiavelli, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Mary Wollstonecraft, and Friedrich Nietzsche, among others.

subject: PSCI
title: Selected World Problems
comments: Our focus in this class will be to study Latin American culture and society through the lens of global interconnections over time, from industrialized global capitalism’s roots in colonial plantations to the construction and reinvention of race in the struggles for independence. To do this, we will engage various fields of inquiry -- from colonial historiography to developmental economics -- as well as analyze, literature, films, music, natural history, and human geography among other topics.

subject: PSCI
title: Selected World Problems
comments: Study Abroad: European Affairs in a Global Context - Riva San Vitale, Switzerland Examines the rise of identity politics in Europe, emphasizing the early to mid-twentieth century as well as the contemporary period.

subject: PSCI
title: Selected World Problems
comments: Topic: European Security & Geopolitics (Military, political, economic, and societal aspects of European security; European geopolitics and geo-economics; European conflicts; US-NATO-EU relations and European security; Russia and European security).

subject: PSYC
title: Special Topics in Dev Psyc
comments: TS: Social Development: The course focuses on major topics in social development during childhood and adolescence. The course is designed to explore theories, methods, and empirical research in social development.

subject: PSYC
title: Senior Seminar
comments: Development in Poverty: This seminar will take a deep look at the profound impact that poverty and many associated factors (e.g., socioeconomic disadvantage, stress, violence, disease, discrimination) has on the developmental well-being of fetuses, infants, and young children around the world.

subject: PSYC
title: Senior Seminar
comments: Myths and Misconceptions in Cognitive and Clinical Science: In this seminar, we will dive into some of the commonly held beliefs about how the brain works and what science can tell us about the brain. We will practice critical reading and thinking based on published materials.

subject: PSYC
title: Senior Seminar
comments: Young Adult Development: This seminar will explore theories and research on development in young adults. Students will discuss characteristics of different generations, and investigate specific topics including mental health, technology, increased focus on diversity, consumerism, entertainment, and interpersonal relationships.

subject: PSYC
title: Senior Seminar
comments: Communicating Science: Students will explore how to create effective writing, presentations, and outreach to engage audiences from different backgrounds and perspectives (including both scientific and lay audiences).

subject: PSYC
title: Senior Seminar
comments: Prosocial and Moral Development: This seminar will examine the development of prosocial behavior and moral reasoning during childhood and adolescence, with a particular emphasis on theories, methods, and research. Topics may include prosocial behavior, moral reasoning, empathy, parenting, and family dynamics.
